Project Title – Open Source Software Audit – Mozilla Firefox

---

1. Introduction

Open Source Software (OSS) has become a core part of modern technology. It allows users to access, modify, and share software freely. This openness encourages innovation, collaboration, and transparency in the software industry.

Mozilla Firefox is one of the most well-known open-source web browsers. It is developed by the Mozilla Foundation with a strong focus on privacy, security, and user freedom. Firefox is widely used across different platforms and plays an important role in maintaining an open and competitive web ecosystem.

This project focuses on analyzing Firefox as an open-source software. It combines theoretical understanding with practical implementation using shell scripting in a Linux (Kali Linux) environment.

---

2. Part A – Origin and Philosophy

A1: Origin of Firefox

Mozilla Firefox was released in 2004 by the Mozilla Foundation. It was developed as a response to the dominance of Internet Explorer, which lacked innovation and had several security issues at that time.

The main goal of Firefox was to provide a faster, safer, and more user-friendly web browsing experience. It introduced modern features such as tabbed browsing, pop-up blocking, and extensions, which significantly improved usability.

Firefox was built with the philosophy of keeping the web open and accessible to everyone, ensuring that no single company controls the internet.

---

A2: License of Firefox

Firefox is distributed under the **Mozilla Public License (MPL 2.0)**.

This license allows users to:

* Use the software freely
* Modify the source code
* Distribute modified versions

Firefox supports the four fundamental freedoms of open-source software:

1. Freedom to run the software
2. Freedom to study the code
3. Freedom to modify it
4. Freedom to share it

The MPL license ensures that modifications to the code remain open while still allowing flexibility for developers.

---

A3: Ethics of Open Source

Open-source software promotes sharing of knowledge and collaborative development.

Advantages: 
* Encourages innovation
* Enhances transparency
* Builds strong developer communities

Challenges

* Companies may use open-source software for profit
* Managing contributions from large communities can be difficult

Despite these challenges, open source plays a vital role in making technology accessible and fair.

